First, thanks so much for the card free ATM feature. It‚Äôs great that someone, especially a bank of your size, is actually trying to innovate in the US banking system.Your app requires multiple security checks to setup for card free ATM access. Then once it‚Äôs setup, I can login using my fingerprint/face on iOS.You still ensure the phone hasn‚Äôt been compromised by additionally asking for a PIN on the ATM itself.Your app also asks for my location via GPS.So then I walk to my ***usual*** ATM with my girlfriend before going to an activity that required cash, and I try to withdraw my usual amount in the usual denominations...And it declines! WtfDo I get a text message telling me about suspected fraud? No. Email? No. Phone call? No. In app notification? No.So I call the number on the ATM...Enter your account number or debit card number it demands. Well I don‚Äôt have my debit card on my person, hence the whole point of the card free ATM feature.I don‚Äôt have a debit card. When I receive it I cut it up for security. I use the card free ATM feature. This is the only way I get access to physical cash as I only carry credit cards + my id.After pressing 0 so many times, I get put on hold for 15 minutes while I hear about how much you care about your customers.The CSR asks for my SSN which I tell her. She looks up my account and then asks for the last four digits of my SSN ‚Äúfor security‚Äù. WTF?!She then asks for 2nd factor auth by text message. I give her the code. She asks me to confirm my attempted withdrawal, which I do. Then she tries to ask me to confirm my identity again via the same 2nd factor (wtf)I finally get access to my money. She asks if there‚Äôs anything else she can do. I tell her this is the 2nd tome this has happened at the same Wells Fargo ATM. An ATM I have used multiple times over several years.She then goes on a rant about how I need to notify you about travel in advance. And how I can do it in the app.***Well yes, but anyone who had access to my phone could give you a travel notification just as easily as they could ask for the card free ATM code.***

Wells Fargo's system went down recently and it's been a cause for concern for me. I recently moved to the US and chose Wells Fargo because it was close to my home, but when the system went down a week or so ago I kept getting fraud alert texts from them. I was fine with the text messages and to a certain extent am okay with the system going down, but when trying to investigate these fraud alerts by calling the Wells Fargo number I had to basically input my card info and password over the phone. How safe is this?? Before coming to the States I used to bank with HSBC. HSBC provided you with a little digital code generator to use when you needed to speak with someone over the phone or to access your online banking. They started doing this like 10 years ago. I believe most Asian banks provide this kind of service. Are all US banks stuck in the dark ages with having to provide your sensitive info over the phone??
